sentences: Blaine Larsen (born February 2, 1986) is an American country music artist.

They then flew him back Nashville again to hold a recording session with him, and by 2004, his debut album In My High School was released on Feek and Johnson's label, Giantslayer Records.
The album's lead-off single, which was the title track, received some airplay particularly in Seattle also reaching 60 on the country charts that year.
Galante auditioned him and agreed to sign him at the end of 2004.
BNA then added a bonus track to In My High School, re-releasing the album in early 2005 under the title Off to Join the World.
In 2006, Larsen released his second studio album, also a joint effort between BNA and Giantslayer.
Entitled Rockin' You Tonight, this album produced two more chart singles for Larsen: the 24 "I Don't Know What She Said" and the 42 "Spoken Like a Man".

Rockin' You Tonight also included covers of Mac Davis "Baby, Don't Get Hooked on Me" and Mark Chesnutt's "I'm in Love with a Married Woman", as well as a duet with Gretchen Wilson entitled "Lips of a Bottle".
He also recorded separately a cover of "I Wish That I Could Fall in Love Today" on a tribute album to Barbara Mandrell.
Larsen exited BNA in 2008, and signed to Treehouse Records, a label founded by his management company, in June 2009.
Larsen exited BNA in 2008, and signed to Treehouse Records, a label founded by his management company, in June 2009.
After one year of operations, Treehouse Records merged in Stroudavarious Records.
A lead-off single from the prospective album, entitled "It Did," made its chart debut in August 2009.
When he was five years old, his parents divorced; he, his mother Jenny, and his sister Lindsey then moved to Buckley, Washington.
A family friend named Woody who worked side jobs as a contractor took Blaine Larsen with him on weekend jobs.
Larsen married Sammie in December 2005.
They had their first daughter Zoe in April 2007.
They had their second child, a son they named Noble in April 2011.
Larsen became an ambassador for Compassion International and in 2010 went to a one-week trip with the organization to Colombia, also sponsoring one of the Colombian kids he met during his mission.
